picoctf Echo Valley writeup

1.we see there is printf(buf) , this can be used format string attack

2.so we use "checksec --file=valley" to check some defense used by this binary

3.it almost open all defense but we can know that we just need to change return address in the stack 

4.so write a python script (echo_valley.py)

5.calculae offset , just use AAAA,%p,%p,%p,%p,%p,%p,%p,%p,%p,%p,%p,%p,%p to analyze its stack

6.get return address because it opens aslr and pie , so we need to leak it

7.we can use "objdump -M intel -d valley" to anslyze how far does [rbp-0x70] (rsp) to [rbp+0x8] (return address position) 

8.know there is 21th in the stack , so we input %21$p to leak the 0x1314 
    140e:       e8 f4 fe ff ff          call   1307 <echo_valley>
    1413:       b8 00 00 00 00          mov    eax,0x0

9.and then we can get the base , so we just use base to get address of print_flag address

10.now , we also need to know where the return address is stored (rbp+0x8)

11.just leak the stack saved_rbp , use %20$p (you can check if this is saved_rbp by looking it whether is started with 0xff)

12.so now we can write print_flag_addr on saved_rbp_addr + 8
# if you use fmtstr_payload , you need to add a requirement which is write_size='short' because buf is not big

